definition.value: A hydrochloride salt resulting from the reaction of equimolar quantities of oxymetazoline and hydrogen chloride. A direct-acting sympathomimetic with marked alpha-adrenergic activity, it is a vasoconstrictor that is used to relieve nasal congestion.
A retinoate that is the conjugate base of 9-cis-retinoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A chromanol that is chromane in which the hydrogen at position 6 is replaced by a hydroxy group.
A fatty alcohol containing 13 carbons and 1 double bond.
A fatty alcohol containing 14 carbons and 1 double bond.
A fatty alcohol containing 15 carbons and 1 double bond.
A fatty alcohol containing 16 carbons and 1 double bond.

A flavonoid oxoanion that is the conjugate base of vitexin 2''-O-beta-L-rhamnoside obtained by deprotonation of the OH group at position 7 on the chromene. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A fatty alcohol containing 17 carbons and 1 double bond.
A fatty alcohol containing 24 carbons and 1 double bond. Formula is C24H48O.
A fatty alcohol containing 26 carbons and 1 double bond.

A 3-oxo-5alpha- steroid that is 4,5alpha-dihydrotestosterone which is substituted by a hydroxymethylidene group at position 2 and by a methyl group at the 17alpha position. A synthetic androgen, it was mainly used for the treatment of anaemias until being replaced by treatments with fewer side effects.
A flavonoid oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the 5-hydroxy group of 7-O-methylvitexin 2''-O-beta-L-rhamnoside. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A fatty alcohol containing 28 carbons and 1 double bond.
A fatty alcohol containing 30 carbons and 1 double bond.
A fatty alcohol containing 20 carbons and 2 double bonds.
A fatty alcohol containing 22 carbons and 2 double bonds.
A fatty alcohol containing 18 carbons and 3 double bonds. Formula is C18H32O.
A sphingomyelin 34:1 in which the N-acyl group and sphingoid base are specified as hexadecanoyl and sphingosine respectively.
A sphingomyelin 34:0 in which the N-acyl group and sphingoid base are specified as hexadecanoyl and sphinganine respectively.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-edelfosine.
A sphingomyelin 34:0 in which the N-acyl group and sphingoid base are specified as hexadecanoyl and phytosphingosine respectively.
A sphingomyelin that is phytosphingosine-1-phosphocholine having an unspecified fatty acyl group attached to the nitrogen.
A glycerophosphocholine that is glycero-3-phosphocholine substituted at positions 1 and 2 by octadecyl and methyl groups respectively.
A 1-octadecyl-2-methylglycero-3-phosphocholine that is the (R)-enantiomer of edelfosine.
An N-acylsphinganine-1-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the N-acyl group is specified as hexadecanoyl.
A ceramide phosphoethanolamine zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phospho to the amino group of any N-acylsphinganine-1-phosphoethanolamine; major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acylphytosphingosine-1-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the N-acyl group is specified as hexadecanoyl.
A ceramide phosphoethanolamine zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phospho to the amino group of any N-acylphytosphingosine-1-phosphoethanolamine; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1-octadecyl-2-methylglycero-3-phosphocholine that is the (S)-enantiomer of edelfosine.
A diol that is propane 1,3-diol bearing additional amino and 4-nitrophenyl substituents at positions 2 and 1 respectively.
A macrolide that is isolated from several Streptomyces species and displays antibiotic, antineoplastic and antimalarial properties.
A squalene triterpenoid obtained by formal epoxidation across the 2,3 C=C bond of squalene.
A polyunsaturated fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate functions of (5Z,11Z,14Z)-icosatrienoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate functions of (5Z,11Z,14Z,17Z)-icosatetraenoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.

A mixture secreted by the hypopharyngeal gland of young worker bees (Apis mellifera) and fed as it is secreted to the queen bee and to larvae that are being raised as potential queen bees; it is not stored. Water makes up about two thirds of fresh royal jelly, with the remainder consisting mostly of proteins and sugars, followed by lipids (mostly free fatty acids containing short (8 to 10 carbon atom) chains with uncommon structures) and water-soluble vitamins.
A 3-oxo-5beta-steroid that is 5beta-pregnan-3-one carrying an additional 20alpha-hydroxy substituent.
An inorganic sodium salt in which chlorite is the counterion.

An omega-hydroxy amino acid that is 2-decenoic acid in which one of the hydrogens attached to the terminal carbon is replaced by a hydroxy group and in which the C=C double bond has E configuration. It is a component of royal jelly.
An aldehyde that is the acyclic form of ascarylose.
An acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate functions of (8Z,11Z)-eicosadienoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An inorganic sodium salt consisting of sodium and chromate ions in a 2:1 ratio.
An inorganic chloride composed of rubidium and chloride ions in a 1:1 ratio.
A peroxol that is cumene in which the alpha-hydrogen is replaced by a hydroperoxy group.
An organobromine compound that is bromobenzene in which the hydrogens at positions 2 and 5 are replaced by 4-hydroxystyryl groups.
Any metabolite produced by all living cells.
A quinolone that is quinoline-5,8-dione in which the hydrogen at position 6 is replaced by an anilino group.
An EC 4.6.* (P-O lyase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of enzyme guanylate cyclase (EC 4.6.1.2).
